c. New topics include death doulas, death tourism, psychogenic death, bonds between the living and the dead, mass death events, and cultural diversity, sensitivity, and competence. This edition combines current research and language used to destigmatize conversations surrounding suicide, while new case studies offer personal accounts from doctors, nurses, and family members of the deceased. Exploring the significance of end-of-life experiences, Dying and Death in Canada shows that how we live influences how we die, and the society and culture in which we live has a profound effect on how we behave when confronted with dying and death.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBereavementxPsychological aspects. 0aDeathxPsychological aspects. 0aDeathxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aDeathzCanada. 0aElectronic books. 0aGrief. 0aLoss (Psychology). 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aaging.  abereavement.  adeath.  adying.  aend of life.  agrief.  agrieving.  ahealth and medicine.  ahealthcare.  amedical assistance in dying.  amedical assisted.  amedical ethics.  amourning.  apalliative care.  asuicide.1 aWilson, Donna , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148750928640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487509286423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487509286/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles